        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4417032233" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16555094847356521093"><i>Living Dead Girl</i> is a jarring, awful novella that&apos;s also essential in its depth and awareness of recognizing signs of a minor being abused, trafficked or kidnapped. Narrator and protagonist &quot;Alice&quot; lives in two worlds: the normal world where she&apos;s almost free, if not for the invisible chains that bind her, and the hell on earth she faces every day from her kidnapper, who has tried to keep her a child in appearance for as long as he&apos;s known her. Alice knows that Ray is a pedophile and that he&apos;s o</span>
  <span id="freeText16555094847356521093" style="display:none"><i>Living Dead Girl</i> is a jarring, awful novella that's also essential in its depth and awareness of recognizing signs of a minor being abused, trafficked or kidnapped. Narrator and protagonist "Alice" lives in two worlds: the normal world where she's almost free, if not for the invisible chains that bind her, and the hell on earth she faces every day from her kidnapper, who has tried to keep her a child in appearance for as long as he's known her. Alice knows that Ray is a pedophile and that he's on the verge of hunting for another victim. She also longs for the day when Ray finally disposes of her, fearing that if she flees, her biological family will be in danger. It's a confusing, ugly and frightening terrain Alice walks through every day... but when it comes to her own ethics and morality, things she's never considered for as long as she's not been herself, she has to make the ultimate self-choice between right and wrong.<br /><br />Stolen from a Seaworld-esque theme park when she was just a little girl, Alice's awareness of society is patchy and stained with the remnants of abuse and mistreatment. <i>Living Dead Girl</i> effectively gives a voice to the voiceless, and while it can definitely be said that the book's content is uncomfortable at best, it can't be ignored, in part because girls and boys just like "Alice" abound in real-life situations. Steven Stayner, Tina Marie Risico, Chip St. Clair... these are just a few of many minor children who've lived with pure evil, and their voices are often reduced to brief news interviews and TV movies. <br /><br /><i>Living Dead Girl</i> is poetic in its prose, and can even be beautiful at times, mostly when Alice dreams of salvation and finds brief snippets of happiness in her otherwise traumatic life. At other times, the book is creepy, haunting and horrific beyond words. One way or another, it gets its ultimate message across, while leaving readers with a new knowledge of the truth of kidnapping victims... that they could be anyone, that they could look almost normal, and that they're in desperate need of our recognition.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16555094847356521093" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

